{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ring Final Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A power circuit that forms a complete loop, starting and ending at the same point in the consumer unit.",
      "anchor": "Think of a 'ring road' where electricity can travel two ways to reach a socket.",
      "misconception": "Thinking any circuit with multiple sockets is a ring; a ring must physically return to its starting point."
    },
    {
      "term": "Radial Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit that runs from the consumer unit to the final point like a branch, without returning to the start.",
      "anchor": "Like a 'dead-end street' where the power travels to the end and stops.",
      "misconception": "Believing radial circuits are only for lighting; they are also used for high-power appliances like cookers."
    },
    {
      "term": "SWA (Steel Wire Armoured)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A heavy-duty cable with a layer of steel wires for mechanical protection against impact and crushing.",
      "anchor": "The 'armoured' cable used for underground runs or industrial workshop floors.",
      "misconception": "Thinking SWA is only for burial; it is required anywhere there is a high risk of physical damage."
    },
    {
      "term": "MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A fireproof cable using copper conductors inside a copper sheath, insulated with compressed mineral powder.",
      "anchor": "The 'ultimate fire-resistant' cable used for emergency alarms and high-heat areas.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it is just a standard thick cable; it is a specialized system that can survive a building fire."
    },
    {
      "term": "Control Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit used to send signals or commands to other equipment rather than providing main power.",
      "anchor": "Like a thermostat 'telling' a boiler to turn on, rather than powering the boiler itself.",
      "misconception": "Assuming control circuits carry the same high current as power circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wiring Enclosure",
      "simpleDefinition": "Protective tubing (conduit) or trunking (casing) used to house and protect cables from the environment.",
      "anchor": "The 'protective shell' that keeps cables safe in commercial or industrial buildings.",
      "misconception": "Thinking trunking is just for tidiness; it provides essential mechanical protection and fire containment."
    },
    {
      "term": "Hazardous Environment",
      "simpleDefinition": "A location where there is a risk of explosion due to the presence of flammable gases, vapors, or dust.",
      "anchor": "A petrol station forecourt or a chemical processing plant.",
      "misconception": "Thinking 'hazardous' just means 'dangerous' (like a construction site); it specifically refers to explosive atmospheres."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Ring final circuits loop back to the source.",
    "Radial circuits end at the last point of use.",
    "SWA provides mechanical protection in industrial zones.",
    "MICC is used for fire-resistant applications.",
    "Agricultural environments require protection against moisture and livestock impact."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Ring and radial circuits are interchangeable terms.",
    "Domestic-grade cables are suitable for industrial environments if hidden.",
    "Control circuits carry the main power load of a system.",
    "Hazardous environments have the same wiring requirements as standard industrial sites."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-3a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Principles of Circuit Types",
      "objective": "Describe the operational principles of common circuit types including ring final, radial, and control circuits.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In electrical installations, we categorize circuits by how they deliver power and their specific function. A Radial Circuit is the most straightforward design; it runs from the consumer unit to the final point of use like a dead-end street. If the cable is cut, everything after that point loses power. Radials are commonly used for lighting, high-power appliances like cookers, or small power runs. In contrast, a Ring Final Circuit forms a complete loop, starting and ending at the same terminals in the consumer unit. This allows electricity to travel two ways to reach a socket, effectively sharing the load across two paths. This is unique to UK power circuits and allows for more sockets on a single circuit.",
        "Beyond standard power, we use Control Circuits to send signals or commands—like a thermostat telling a boiler to fire—rather than carrying the main power load. Specialized circuits also exist for data communications and emergency systems. Emergency lighting circuits, for example, must operate differently to ensure they remain functional during a power failure. Using the correct circuit type is vital; mistaking a radial for a ring or using a control circuit for a power load can lead to overloaded conductors and system failure."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether the cable returns to the consumer unit to form a loop or ends at the last socket."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-3a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Wiring Systems and Environments",
      "objective": "Identify appropriate wiring systems for domestic, commercial, industrial, agricultural, and hazardous environments.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Selecting a wiring system depends entirely on the environmental stresses it will face. In a domestic setting, we typically use thermoplastic multicore flat profile cable (often called twin and earth) hidden within walls. However, this lacks the mechanical strength needed for an industrial workshop. For areas with a high risk of impact or crushing, we use SWA (Steel Wire Armoured) cable or single-core cables protected by a wiring enclosure like steel conduit or trunking. These enclosures act as a protective shell against physical damage and can also help contain fire.",
        "In specialized environments, the requirements become stricter. For fire alarms or emergency systems, we use MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad) cable because it is fireproof and can survive extreme heat. Agricultural environments require systems that can withstand moisture, chemicals, and impact from livestock. Finally, a Hazardous Environment, such as a petrol station forecourt, requires specific containment systems to prevent sparks from igniting flammable vapors or dust. You must never assume domestic-grade cables are suitable for industrial or hazardous sites; matching the cable's physical properties to the environment is a fundamental safety requirement."
      ],
      "hint": "Consider the level of mechanical protection and fire resistance required for the specific location."
    }
  ]
}

