{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Synthesize knowledge of circuit topologies and wiring system durability to design a safe installation for a multi-environment industrial facility.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To wrap this up, you need to look at an installation as a whole. You aren't just 'running cables'; you are matching the circuit's operational principle (how it carries power or signals) with a wiring system that can survive the specific environment.",
      "Consider a site that includes an industrial workshop and a hazardous fuel storage area. You must ensure the sockets can handle the load, the emergency systems can survive a fire, and the equipment in the hazardous zone won't cause an explosion."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are designing the electrical layout for a site with an industrial workshop and a hazardous fuel storage area. Specify the most appropriate circuit type and wiring system for the following three requirements: \n1) A loop of 12 sockets on the workshop floor where heavy machinery is moved and mechanical impact is a high risk. \n2) The emergency exit lighting system that must remain functional during a fire. \n3) The signaling link for the fuel pump controls located within the hazardous zone.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "1) Workshop Sockets: Ring Final Circuit (to share the load across the loop) using SWA (Steel Wire Armoured) or single-core cables in steel conduit/trunking for mechanical protection.",
      "2) Emergency Lighting: Radial Circuit (dedicated run) using MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad) or fire-resistant cable to ensure operation during a fire.",
      "3) Fuel Pump Controls: Control Circuit (for signaling) using specialized hazardous-area-rated wiring systems (such as SWA or conduit with appropriate seals) to prevent ignition of flammable vapors."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which circuit type allows for a 'loop' of sockets, which cable is specifically fireproof (MICC), and which environment requires protection against explosive vapors."
  }
}

